Bacteria
definition: Bacteria are a large domain of single-celled, prokaryote microorganisms. Some species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy and bubonic plague. The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections, with tuberculosis alone killing about 2 million people a year, mostly in sub-Saharan Africa. Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and in agriculture, yet antibiotic resistance is becoming increasingly common.

Virus
definition: Viruses are a large domain of infectious agents consisting typically of a nucleic acid molecule surrounded in a protein coat, sometimes with a peptide molecule. Viruses are highly variable and are capable of infecting all forms of life, with many different mechanisms. Some viruses are bacteriophage viruses, which infect a bacterial cell and reproduce within the cell, causing cell lysis and killing the bacterium.
